{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.05,0.24,0.08,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43558"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28572"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1223"},{"type":"tags","id":"4566"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44091"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43558"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to her General Practitioner with her father concerned about the pimples on her face. She is embarrassed by this and gets teased at school by her classmates. She is otherwise well, has no medical conditions or allergies and takes no regular medications. On examination her acne affects her forehead and chin region only. There are three small isolated closed comedones on her forehead and five inflamed pustules on her chin. Some have surrounding erythema and evidence of scabbing. There is no scarring.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical adapalene","Oral erythromycin","Oral doxycycline","Oral isotretinoin","Combined oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe above stem describes typical mild acne affecting an adolescent. This is extremely common and often occurs during pre- or pubertal periods. It is important to assess the psychological impact that the acne is having and also assess the severity to determine which management option would be most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor mild acne in adolescents topical preparations are first line. Over the counter benzoyl peroxide creams or gels at 2.5-5% can be used. These are safe, easy for patients to access and can have a good response in many patients. Another topical option for mild acne is a topical retinoid such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eadapalene\u003C/strong\u003E. They often take up to six weeks for a response to be seen. Benzoyl peroxide can also be combined in a gel with topical retinoids or topical antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor more severe acne of if other topical methods have failed oral antibiotics such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral doxycycline \u003C/strong\u003Eor\u003Cstrong\u003E oral erythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E can be trialled. Antibiotics, whether topical or oral are used for their anti-inflammatory action as acne is not an infection. Tetracyclines are considered first line, unless they cannot be tolerated or it is a pregnant female.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe above options can be combined in some cases such as topical benzoyl peroxide +\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ea topical retinoid OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ea topical antibiotic such as clindamycin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf these all fail, or the acne is moderate to severe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral \u003C/strong\u003Eretinoids such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eisotretinoin\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered. Retinoids are the most effective treatment for acne, but they have side effects. They should be avoided in all women who are planning to become pregnant, are pregnant or are breastfeeding. They are teratogenic and this must be explained to all female patients if they are prescribed this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother option to avoid antibiotics and retinoids in females is starting the\u003Cstrong\u003E combined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E for moderate to severe acne. A six month trial is recommended to see results and also offers the benefit of contraception if the patient is seeking an option for this as well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case her acne is described as mild as suggested by the description of her acne \u2013 it is isolated to the forehead and chin, she has \u0026lt;30 lesions and there is no scarring. Therefore, a topical option would be the best first line option, such as benzoyl peroxide. If this fails other topical options can be considered at a later stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Topical benzoyl peroxide or a retinoid are good first line options for mild acne.","Retinoids are teratogenic.","Oral antibiotics (such as doxycycline) are used to treat acne for their anti-inflammatory properties."],"references":["Titus S, Hodge J. Diagnosis and Treatment of Acne. Am Fam Physician. 2012; 86:734-40."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28572"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28572"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-22T17:37:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T18:41:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43558"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":